		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Providence</placeName> <date>Oct 4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1858</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Editor of the Occident <placeName>Phila</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Rev. Sir&#33;</p>
				<p>It is considerable time that you did<lb/> not hear anything from me&#44; for the<lb/> Reason that I had nothing particular<lb/> to communicate.  But now I have<lb/> a very interesting affair to report.<lb/>  At our <sic>anual</sic> Election for officers<lb/> of our Congregation &#8222;Bnai Israel&#8221; our<lb/> worthy President <persName>Mr. Solomon Pareira</persName><lb/> my respected father in Law after having<lb/> served this Congregation over 3 years as<lb/> President deduced another nomination.<lb/>  The Congregation deeply impressed with his<lb/> faithful and many services rendered<lb/> in establishing a congregation here&#44;<lb/> resolved to present him with a Beautiful<lb/> Silver Goblet and to his excellent wife<lb/> a Silver Sugar Bowl.  This important<lb/> affair came off last <date>Sunday</date> morning<lb/>  The several members heard by my<lb/> humble self at the Chairman of the Trustees<lb/> and <persName>Mr. Moses Bernhard</persName> our nearly elected<lb/> <sic>Secratary</sic> and Treasurer heading the procession</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>marched to the House of our worthy Ex&#45;<lb/>President where we presented him the Goblet<lb/> and the Engraved <sic>Adress</sic> with a Speech<lb/> from my humble self of the latter<lb/> will not say much as it was only a<lb/> poor but well meant speech.<lb/>  An excellent oration was delivered then<lb/> by our worthy Chasau <persName>Mr. Moses Cohen</persName><lb/> formerly from <placeName>England</placeName>.  <persName>Mr. Pareira</persName><lb/> as well as <sic>she</sic> was altogether taken<lb/> by surprise.  Our worthy&#39;s Expresident<lb/> <sic>hearts</sic> was to full to utter all his<lb/> feelings at that moment&#44; he tried it<lb/> but the emotion over came him.  His young<lb/> son <persName>Mr. Isaac Pareira</persName> responded<lb/> very ably in behalf of his father<lb/> After that we had another religious dis&#45;<lb/>course from <persName>Mr. Cohen</persName> and then a<lb/> Kadish from an Ofal<add>&#63;</add> and after this<lb/> a regular jolly time.  So ended this<lb/> worthy and well deserved Testimonial<lb/> for the Benefit of your numerous Readers<lb/> I&#39;ll give you on the other page the contents<lb/> of the <sic>adress</sic> and the Inscription of the<lb/> Goblet.  You will hear soon again from<lb/> me.  I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)">Yours humble friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">J. R Hershry</persName></p>
			<pb n="2R"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">Inscription of the Goblet</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">To our worthy Brother and</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">Ex president <persName>Solomon Pareira</persName></p>
				<p rend="align(center)">by</p>
				<p>his friends</p>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Prov.</placeName> <date>Oct. 3d. 1858</date></p>
				<p rend="align(center)">&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">Contents of the Engraved <sic>Adress</sic></p>
				<p rend="align(center)">To</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">our worthy Brother and Ex President</p>
				<p rend="align(center)"><persName>Solomon Pareira</persName></p>
				<p>The Undersigned being deeply impressed with the great<lb/> and many Services you so cheerfully rendered in Establ<lb/>ising and maintaining <del>this</del> our Synagogue during the most<lb/> trying times the patience&#44; kindness and forbearance you<lb/> <sic>excercised</sic> while our presiding officers and the willing<lb/>ness you always showed to assist and help others I take<lb/> this opportunity at your retiring from the office you<lb/> so <sic>worhtyly</sic> filled for the last 3 years to present to<lb/> you the accompanying Testimonial</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">A Goblet.</p>
				<p>which your Lot may it be always to see filled<lb/> to the Brim with the wine of happiness health<lb/> and prosperity which you may greaff<add>&#63;</add> constantly for<lb/> a great number of years yet and still it may never<lb/> become less.  Be assured dear sir that<lb/> wherever you may live that our best and kind<lb/> wishes will always accompany you.</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Respectfully your friends</p>
				<p><persName>J R Hersom</persName>&#44; <persName>Moses Bernhard</persName>&#44; <persName>L. Halberetad</persName>&#44; <persName>D<lb/> Stark</persName>. <persName>B. Shuman</persName> <persName>Henry Solomons</persName>&#44; <persName>E. Myers</persName>&#44; <persName>H. Green</persName>.<lb/> <persName>A Myerson</persName> <persName>R. frank<add>&#63;</add></persName></p>
		
